    "recap_headline": "Quinnipiac University",
    "recap_text": "Hamden, Conn. \u2013\nThe Quinnipiac Bobcats scored 11 runs in the fifth inning to power them past the Yale Bulldogs on Wednesday afternoon in Hamden. Quinnipiac put up a total of 15 runs as they improved to 6-11 on the season.\nSCORE\nQuinnipiac 15, Yale 9\nRECORDS\nQuinnipiac (6-11, 1-2 MAAC) | Yale (8-6, 0-0 IVY)\nWinning Pitcher \u2013\nJosh Lajoie\n(1-0)\nLosing Pitcher \u2013\u00a0Nick West (0-1)\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nThe Yale Bulldogs came to play in the opening inning, striking for six runs to give them an early lead in this one.\nYale tacked on another run in the second inning as they took the field in the bottom half with a seven-run lead. Quinnipiac got a run back as\nChase Camac\ngrounded out, allowing\nChristian Smith\nto come home with the Bobcats' first run of the game.\nYale answered right back in the third inning, scoring two more runs as their lead was 9-1 after the first three innings of play.\nThe score would remain 9-1 until the home half of the fifth inning, when the Bobcats' offense exploded for eleven runs in the inning.\nCaden Williamson\nstarted the scoring in the inning, singling home\nIan Nilsen\nwith their second run of the game. Quinnipiac tacked on another run as\nMatt Park\ncame home on a\nKyle Garbowski\nsingle. With only one out in the inning,\nAlex Irizarry\nhit a sac fly to bring QU within five. Now with two away in the inning,\nChristian Smith\ndelivered with a two-run double down the left field line, bringing the Bobcats within four.\nChase Camac\nwould make it a two-run game as he scored two more runs on a single to center field.\nJames Marino\ncame in to score on a passed ball to make it a one-run game, and\nMatt Park\nwould knot it up at nine with a single to right field. With two outs and two runners on,\nBrayden Hromada\nlaunched his first collegiate homer to put the Bobcats in front for the first time of the afternoon.\nLater in the seventh inning, Quinnipiac pushed their lead to 15-9.\nCaden Williamson\nflew out to center, scoring\nIan Nilsen\nfrom third for the first run of the inning. Later in the inning, Irizarry singled to left center, scoring another two runs and giving the Bobcats a six-run lead.\nNEWS AND NOTES\nEight different Bobcats recorded hits in the series comeback win over Yale. Of those eight batters, five recorded multiple hits.\nCaden Williamson\n,\nMatt Park\n, and\nBrayden Hromada\neach picked up three hits in the win.\nHromada went 3-for-5 at the dish, recording his first collegiate base hit, extra-base hit, home run, and run batted in in the win over Yale.\nChase Camac\nand\nAlex Irizarry\npicked up a hit in the win but drove in three RBIs each.\nChristian Smith\nreturned to the lineup and went 2-for-5 with two doubles, two runs scored, and an RBI.\nKyle Garbowski\nhad a multi-hit day, recording two hits in five at-bats out of the two hole.\nIan Nilsen\ndrew three walks and recorded one hit in two at-bats, while scoring three runs.\nThe Bobcats sent seven different pitchers to the mound in the win over Yale.\nJosh Lajoie\nearned the win, going 2.0 innings in relief, striking out two and not allowing a run.\nEthan Freed\nthrew two scoreless innings behind Lajoie, lowering his ERA to 2.70.\nNick Balcom\nfollowed up with a scoreless eighth inning, and\nMatt Alduino\nshut it down in the ninth to seal the win.\nAlduino held the Bulldogs off the board as he lowered his season ERA to 2.25.\nON DECK\nThe Bobcats will head on the road, taking on the Manhattan Jaspers in a three-game series at Clover Stadium in Pomona, New York."
  },
